The '''Isle of Portland''' is a {{convert|4|mi|km|0|lk=on|sing=on|mos=on}}  long by {{convert|1.5|mi|km|1|sing=on}} wide [[limestone]] island in the [[English Channel]]. The isle is {{convert|5|mi|km|0|mos=on}} south of the resort of [[Weymouth]], forming the southernmost point of the [[counties of England|county]] of [[Dorset]], in [[England]], [[United Kingdom]]. The island is connected to the mainland by a large pebble [[tombolo]], [[Chesil Beach]], and by the [[A354 road]] bridge to Weymouth. Portland had a population of 12,710 in 2005, and is part of the borough of [[Weymouth and Portland]].

The island is a central part of the [[Jurassic Coast]] World Heritage Site, a {{convert|95|mi|km|0|sing=on}} long stretch of the Dorset and east Devon coast, important for its varied geology and landforms.  The island's name is used for one of the [[British Sea Areas]], and has been [[Portland|exported]] as the name of several North American cities and Australian towns.  High quality [[Portland limestone]], still quarried here, has been used extensively in British architecture, including [[St Paul's Cathedral]] and the [[United Nations Building]].

Portland is notable for its large, deep artificial [[Portland Harbour|harbour]] which was an important [[Royal Navy]] base during [[World War I]] and [[World War II]], and a key Royal Navy and [[North Atlantic Treaty Organisation|NATO]] training base until the 1990s, and is now a small civilian port and popular recreation area.  England's [[National Sailing Academy]] is situated in the harbour and will host the sailing events for the [[2012 Olympic Games]].

==History==
[[Image:Porland island map1937.jpg|thumb|220px|image|left|A map of the Isle of Portland from 1937]]
Portland has been inhabited since at least the [[Mesolithic]] period (the Middle [[Stone Age]]) - there is [[archaeological]] evidence of Mesolithic inhabitants near [[Portland Bill]],<ref name="mesolithic">{{cite web | last = | first = | authorlink = | coauthors = | year = 2002 | url = http://www.gallica.co.uk/celts/portland.htm | title =  Mesolithic Site, Portland | format = | work = | publisher = Association for Portland Archaeology | accessdate = 2007-07-30}}</ref> and there is evidence of inhabitation of the island in ages since. The island was occupied by the [[Roman Empire|Romans]], who reputedly called the Island ''Vindelis''.<ref name="vindelis">{{cite web | last = | first = | authorlink = | coauthors = | year = 2006 | url = http://www.uni-mannheim.de/mateo/camenaref/hofmann/hof4/s0773b.html | title =  Lexicon Universale | format = | work = | publisher = Universitat Mannheim | accessdate = 2007-04-03}}</ref><ref name="Portland stone" /> [[Portland Castle]] was built by [[Henry VIII of England|King Henry VIII]] in 1539 in response to attacks by [[France]], costing [[Pound Sterling|£]]4,964 to construct.<ref name="portlandcastle">{{cite web | last = | first = | authorlink = | coauthors = | year = 2000 | url = http://www.thedorsetpage.com/locations/Place/P120.htm | title =  Portland, Dorset, England | format = | work = | publisher = The Dorset Page | accessdate = 2007-07-26}}</ref> It is one of the best preserved [[castle]]s from this period of British history, and is now open to the public under the administration of [[English Heritage]].<ref name="englishheritage">{{cite web | last = | first = | authorlink = | coauthors = | year = 2007 | url = http://www.english-heritage.org.uk/server/show/nav.15746 | title =  Portland Castle | format = | work = | publisher = English Heritage | accessdate = 2007-07-30}}</ref>

The Crown opened many of the [[quarry|quarries]] which made Portland famous.  After the [[Great Fire of London]], Sir [[Christopher Wren]], the notable architect and [[Member of Parliament]] for nearby Weymouth, used six million tons of white [[Portland limestone]] to rebuild much of London, and some well-known buildings in the capital, including [[St Paul's Cathedral]]<ref name="st paul's">{{cite web | last = | first = | authorlink = | coauthors = | year = 2007 | url = http://www.stpauls.co.uk/page.aspx?theLang=001lngdef&pointerid=32207NnDnfjeCGJ1g2bvy1Jt3FI0gUAP | title =  1710 - Construction is Completed | format = | work = | publisher = Dean and Chapter St Paul's | accessdate = 2007-04-03}}</ref> and the eastern front of [[Buckingham Palace]].<ref name="buckinghampalace">{{cite web | last = | first = | authorlink = | coauthors = | year = 2007 | url = http://www.royal.gov.uk/output/Page568.asp | title =  Buckingham Palace History | format = | work = | publisher = HM Queen Elizabeth II | accessdate = 2007-04-03}}</ref>. The [[UN Headquarters|headquarters]] of the [[United Nations]] in [[New York City]] also features Portland Stone.<ref name="UNheadquarters">{{cite web | last = | first = | authorlink = | coauthors = | year = 2006 | url = http://www.thebeasts.info/Learning/Portland_Stone/index.htm | title =  Portland Stone | format = | work = | publisher = Harris Digital | accessdate = 2007-07-26}}</ref>  After [[World War I]] a dedicated quarry was opened to provide stone for the [[Whitehall]] [[Cenotaph]] and half a million gravestones for war cemeteries.<ref name="Portland stone">{{cite web | last = | first = | authorlink = | coauthors = | year = 2007 | url = http://www.dorsets.co.uk/Portland/ | title =  Portland - Dorset | format = | work = | publisher = Dorset Guide | accessdate = 2007-04-03}}</ref>  Hundreds of thousands of gravestones were carved for the fallen soldiers of the [[Western Front]] in [[World War II]].<ref name="Portland stone" /> The very popular Portland Cement is not manufactured on Portland; the strong cement mix was a German invention, and was named Portland Cement due to its similar colour to the famous Portland limestone when mixed with lime and sand.<ref name="cement">{{cite web | last = | first = | authorlink = | coauthors = | year = 2007 | url = http://www.cement.org/basics/concretebasics_history.asp | title =  History & Manufacture of Portland Cement | format = | work = | publisher = Portland Cement Association | accessdate = 2007-07-26}}</ref>

[[Image:Dorset pl sp 26.jpg|thumb|Tout Quarry, now disused, became an internationally known sculpture park and nature reserve. Famous sculptors including [[Antony Gormley]] have produced work there.]]
[[Portland harbour]], at {{convert|2130|acre|sqkm|0|lk=on}}, is one of the deepest man-made [[harbour]]s in the world at around 20 metres, and the second largest.<ref name="harbour">{{cite web | last = | first = | authorlink = | coauthors = | year = 2007 | url = http://www.portland-port.co.uk/ppl_index.htm | title =  Portland Port Limited | format = | work = | publisher = Portland Port Limited | accessdate = 2007-07-26}}</ref> The harbour and [[Weymouth Bay]] have an unusual feature: a double low tide, caused by the time it takes for [[high tide]] to round the island, and its [[tidal race]] at the Bill.<ref name="tide">{{cite web | last = | first = | authorlink = | coauthors = | year = 2007 | url = http://www.bristolnomads.org.uk/location_reports/s_coast/portland.htm | title =  Portland Harbour | format = | work = | publisher = Bristol Nomads Windsurfing Club | accessdate = 2007-07-30}}</ref><ref name="tide2">{{cite web | last = | first = | authorlink = | coauthors = | year = 2007 | url = http://www.bbc.co.uk/weather/coast/tides/tides.shtml?date=20070730&loc=0033 | title =  Tides: Portland | format = | work = | publisher = British Broadcasting Corporation | accessdate = 2007-07-30}}</ref> The first stone of the [[Breakwater (structure)|Breakwaters]] was laid by [[Prince Albert of Saxe-Coburg-Gotha|Prince Albert]] in 1849, and the last stone of the first phase by [[Edward VII of the United Kingdom|Albert Edward]], [[Prince of Wales]], in 1872.<ref name="portlandcastle" /> The breakwaters were constructed mainly by civilian contractors, but all the stone was quarried by convicts. 22 men lost their lives during their construction, and by completion the breakwaters contained 5,731,376 [[long ton]]s of stone and cost, in 1871, [[GBP|£]]1,167,852.<ref name="portlandcastle" /> The island is still home to [[Verne (HM Prison)|HMP the Verne]] and [[HMYOI]] Portland, and the harbour contains Britain's only [[prison ship]], [[Weare (HM Prison)|''HMP Weare'']], closed during 2005, but still berthed in the port.

Portland Harbour has housed a [[Royal Navy]] base since it was constructed in 1919 as HMS Serepta.<ref name="serepta">{{cite web | last = | first = | authorlink = | coauthors = | year = 2007 | url = http://www.helis.com/database/?menu=2&tpais=UK&tbase=33&menudiv=1 | title =  Portland Base/Heliport History | format = | work = | publisher = helis.com | accessdate = 2007-07-28}}</ref> As the island and its harbour were home to much of the Royal Navy during [[World War II]], Portland was the target of heavy bombing. To protect the harbour from torpedo and submarine attack, [[HMS Hood (1891)]] was sunk in the Southern Ship Passage between the southern two breakwaters.<ref name="HMShood">{{cite web | last = | first = | authorlink = | coauthors = | year = 2007 | url = http://www.battleships-cruisers.co.uk/hms_hood.htm | title =  Turret Battleship, HMS Hood | format = | work = | publisher = Cranston Fine Arts | accessdate = 2007-07-26}}</ref> In 1946 local playing fields were turned into a heliport, and in 1959 the station was formally commissioned as [[RNAS Portland (HMS Osprey)|HMS Osprey]]; the base was gradually improved with the addition landing areas and one of [[England]]'s shortest runways, at 229 [[metre]]s.<ref name="serepta" /> 

Much of the naval base closed at the end of the [[Cold War]] in 1995, and the Royal Naval Air Station closed in 1999, whilst the runway remained in use for [[Her Majesty's Coastguard]] Search and Rescue flights as MRCC Portland.<ref name="serepta" /> MRCC Portland's area of responsibility extends midway across the [[English Channel]], and from [[Start Point, Devon|Start Point]] in [[Devon]] to the Dorset/[[Hampshire]] border, covering an area of approximately {{convert|4000|sqmi|sqkm|-2|lk=on}}.<ref name="coastguard">{{cite web | last = | first = | authorlink = | coauthors = | year = 2007 | url = http://www.beercoastguard.org/coastguard_rescue_helicoper.htm | title =  Coastguard Rescue Helicopter | format = | work = | publisher = Beer Coastguard | accessdate = 2007-07-28}}</ref> Last year  the 12 [[Search and Rescue]] teams in the Portland area dealt with almost 1000 incidents;<ref name="mrccportland">{{cite web | last = | first = | authorlink = | coauthors = | year = 2007 | url = http://www.mcga.gov.uk/c4mca/mcga-dops-regional/eastern-region/mcga-dops_rr_east_regional-eastern-region-solent.htm | title =  Eastern Region - Area South | format = | work = | publisher = [[Maritime and Coastguard Agency]] | accessdate = 2007-07-28}}</ref> most teams use [[lifeboat]]s whilst the crew based at Portland have the use of a [[Sikorsky S-61]] [[helicopter]].<ref name="coastguard" />

Since the early 19th Century, Portland has had a number of railway [[branch line]]s. The Merchant's Railway was the earliest, opening in 1826 (one year after the [[Stockton and Darlington railway]]), and ran from the quarries at the north end of the Island to the docks in [[Castletown, Dorset|Castletown]], where Portland stone was shipped around the country.<ref name="railways">{{cite web | last = | first = | authorlink = | coauthors = | year = 2005 | url = http://www.johnrnew.demon.co.uk/weyrails.htm | title =  Railways of the Weymouth area | format = | work = | publisher = Island Publishing | accessdate = 2007-07-26}}</ref> The [[Portland Branch Railway|Weymouth and Portland Railway]] was constructed in 1865, and ran from a [[train station|station]] in [[Melcombe Regis]], across the Fleet and along Chesil Beach to a station in Victoria Square in [[Chiswell]].<ref name="railways2">{{cite web | last = | first = | authorlink = | coauthors = | year = 2007 | url = http://www.weymouth.gov.uk/main.asp?svid=351 | title =  Weymouth to Portland Railway, Construction and growth | format = | work = | publisher = Weymouth and Portland Borough Council | accessdate = 2007-07-26}}</ref> The line continued as the Easton and Church Hope Railway, which circled the island through Castletown and ascended the cliffs at East Weares, to loop back north to a station in [[Easton, Dorset|Easton]].<ref name="railways" /> The line closed to passengers in March 1965, with the final goods train running in April that year.<ref name="railways2" />

[[Image:Chesil Cove.JPG|left|thumb|Chesil Beach protects Chiswell from flooding]]
For many centuries coastal [[flooding]] has affected Chiswell; the village lies below [[sea level]] next to [[Chesil Cove|the terminus]] of Chesil Beach. In autumn and winter Chesil Beach is subject to severe [[storm]]s and massive waves, which have a very long [[fetch (geography)|fetch]] across the entire [[Atlantic Ocean]].<ref name="flooding">{{cite web | last = | first = | authorlink = | coauthors = | year = 2007 | url = http://www.swgfl.org.uk/jurassic/chis10.htm | title =  Chiswell case study: The Scheme | format = | work = | publisher = Jurassic Coast | accessdate = 2007-07-27}}</ref> Following two severe flood events in the 1970s, [[Weymouth and Portland]] Borough Council and [[Wessex Water]] decided to investigate the structure of the beach, and possible [[coastal management]] schemes that could be constructed there to protect Chiswell. In the 1980s it was agreed that a scheme to protect against a [[return period|one-in-five year]] storm would be practicable, which would also reduce flood depth and duration for more severe storms.<ref name="flooding" /> As part of this scheme, several [[Coastal defence#Hard construction techniques|hard engineering]] techniques were employed, including a {{convert|1.6|km|mi|0|sing=on}} [[gabion]] beach crest to the north of Chiswell, an extended [[sea wall]] next to the village itself, and a [[culvert]] running from inside the beach, underneath Portland Beach Road and into [[Portland Harbour]], to divert flood water away from low lying areas.<ref name="flooding" />

[[Rabbit]]s have been associated with [[bad luck]] for centuries on Portland, and as such use of the name is still [[taboo]], with the creatures often being referred to as "Underground Mutton", "Long-Eared Furry Things" or just "bunnies".<ref name="wallaceandgromit">{{cite web | last = | first = | authorlink = | coauthors = | year = 2006 | url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/dorset/4318710.stm  | title = Wallace and Gromit spook island | format = | work = | publisher = [[British Broadcasting Corporation]] | accessdate = 2007-07-26}}</ref> The fear of the word rabbit is popularly believed to derive from workers in the island's quarries, as they would often see rabbits emerging from their [[burrow]]s immediately before a rock fall; the rabbits' burrowing was often blamed for increasing the risk of such dangerous (and sometimes deadly) [[landslide]]s.<ref name="rabbits" /> There have been several instances of cave-ins, and in one instance a [[crane (machine)|crane]] operator died when his crane toppled on weak ground above rabbit burrows. In past times when the quarrying was done by hand, if a rabbit was seen in the area, the quarry man would pack up and go home for the day, until the safety of the area had been assured.<ref name="wallaceandgromit" /> Even today many older Portland residents will be offended or go quiet at the mention of the word rabbit.<ref name="rabbits">{{cite web | last = | first = | authorlink = | coauthors = | year = 2006 | url = http://www.weymouth.gov.uk/main.asp?svid=784  | title = Rabbits, the Portland taboo word | format = | work = | publisher = Weymouth and Portland Borough Council | accessdate = 2007-07-26}}</ref>

This [[superstition]] came to national attention in October 2005 when a special batch of [[movie poster|advertisement posters]] were made for the [[Wallace and Gromit]] film, [[Wallace & Gromit: The Curse of the Were-Rabbit|The Curse of the Were-Rabbit]]. In respect of local beliefs the flim promoters omitted the word 'rabbit' and replaced the film's title with the phrase, ''"Something bunny is going on"''.<ref name="wallaceandgromit" />

==Politics and demographics==
[[Image:DorsetWeymouthPortland.png|thumb|right|Weymouth and Portland shown within Dorset]]
The island is an ancient [[Royal Manor]], and until the [[19th century]] remained a separate [[Liberty (division)|liberty]] within the county for administrative purposes. The entire Isle constituted a single [[urban district]] from 1894 to 1974, when it became part of the [[borough]] of [[Weymouth and Portland]]. Weymouth and Portland was formed on April 1 1974, under the [[Local Government Act 1972]], and was a merger between the nearby borough of Weymouth and Melcombe Regis and the Portland urban district. 

The [[Mayor]] of Weymouth and Portland is David Harris ([[Liberal Democrats|Lib Dem]]), with Tim Munro ([[Independent politician#United Kingdom|Independent]]) as Deputy Mayor Mayor of Portland Town Council.<ref name="weymouthcouncillors">{{cite web | last = | first = | authorlink = | coauthors = | year = 2007 | url = http://www.weymouth.gov.uk/Council/Councillors/home.asp?svid=586 | title = Weymouth and Portland Borough Council - councillors | format = | work = | publisher = Weymouth and Portland Borough Council | accessdate = 2007-07-26}}</ref> Weymouth and Portland and [[Purbeck]] [[district]]s are in the [[Dorset South]] parliamentary [[United Kingdom constituencies|constituency]], created in 1885. The constituency elects one [[Member of Parliament]]. The current MP for Dorset South is [[Jim Knight]] ([[Labour Party (UK)|Labour]]), who is currently [[Minister of State]] for Schools.

